		<body>
			<div type="month" mhs:startingPage="292"  mhs:precedingFile="JQADiaries-v24-1800-03-p290.xml" mhs:followingFile="JQADiaries-v24-1800-05-p294.xml" mhs:volume="24">
				<bibl n="metadata"><date from="1800-04-01" to="1800-04-30"/></bibl>

				<!-- D/JQA/24.2051 -->

				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-01">
					<head>1 April 1800</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04-01"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<dateline><hi rend="italic">April. 1800.</hi></dateline>
						<p><date>1. </date>Weather continues fine— <persRef
								key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
								Adams</persRef> spent the Evening at <persRef ref="vonbruhl-sophia"
								>Countess Brühl’s</persRef>. I was there about an hour.— I have now
							scarcely time for a thought out of the principal thing I have
							undertaken.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-02">
					<head>2 April 1800</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04-02"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>2. </date><persRef ref="arbuthnot-robert">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
								Arbuthnot</persRef> spent the Evening with us— Read to him the
							seventh book of my Oberon. It was so
							long, he probably thought it tedious.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-03">
					<head>3 April 1800</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04-03"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>3. </date><persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Catel</persRef>
							this morning— A long walk before dinner in the park— At least I can take
							more exercise, for being engag’d in my present business; which I can do
							while walking, better than when shut up in a chamber— Yet six Stanza’s
							in a day, I still find a heavy task.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-04">
					<head>4 April 1800</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04-04"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>4. </date>Walk’d morning and afternoon— Spent part of the evening
							at <persRef ref="brown-charles">D<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
								Brown’s</persRef>— <persRef ref="talbot-charles">Lord
								Talbot</persRef> was there— He is on his return to England from a
							tour through Italy, and at Vienna, since I saw him last August at
							Töplitz— Look’d over his collection of prints and drawings.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-05">
					<head>5 April 1800</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04-05"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>5. </date>Took a shorter walk than usual. In the afternoon—
							Burden’d excessively with the ungrateful task of my translation, which I
							have no reason for continuing but that I began it.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-06">
					<head>6 April 1800</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04-06"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<pb n="293" type="ms"/>
						<p><date>6. </date>Read a sermon of <persRef ref="tillotson-john"
								>Tillotson</persRef> this morning— Spent the Evening with <persRef
								key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A.</persRef>
							at the <persRef ref="ofarrillyherrera-gonzalo">Spanish
								Minister’s</persRef>.— On returning home received letters from
								<persRef ref="king-rufus">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> King</persRef>,
							and from America— Finish’d the 8<hi rend="superscript">th:</hi> book of Oberon,
							&amp; began the 9<hi rend="superscript">th:</hi></p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-07">
					<head>7 April 1800</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04-07"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>7. </date>Walk in the afternoon with <persRef
								key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
							A</persRef>—she spent the evening at <persRef ref="brown-mary">M<hi
									rend="superscript">rs:</hi> Brown’s</persRef>. I was there about an
							hour— Miss Brühl was there.— Read part of the first volume of the
							Volksmährchen der Deutschen.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-08">
					<head>8 April 1800</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04-08"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>8. </date>Newspapers and pamphlets from America.— There is not much
							satisfaction in reading them. Walk’d this evening, and met <persRef
								ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> de Sartoris</persRef>— Part of a
							book in the Iliad—</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-09">
					<head>9 April 1800</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04-09"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>9. </date>The weather is almost at summer heat— Long walk in the
							Park— Evening at <persRef ref="u">Countess Golowkin’s</persRef>. Company
							constantly coming and going.— <persRef
								ref="schulenburgkehnert-frederick">Count Schulenburg</persRef>—
							Ridiculous story about <persRef ref="u">Miss Bielfeld</persRef>.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-10">
					<head>10 April 1800</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04-10"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>10. </date>Letters this evening from America.— <persRef ref="u"
									>M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Catel’s</persRef> day— <persRef
								ref="welsh-thomas2">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Welsh</persRef> is quite
							unwell.— Long walk in the park, and again towards Evening under the
							trees. <persRef ref="brown-mary">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
								Brown’s</persRef>
							<persRef
								ref="brown-charles;brown-william5;brown-isabella;brown-fanny;brown-margaret"
								>family</persRef>, and <persRef ref="garlike-benjamin">M<hi
									rend="superscript">r:</hi> Garlike</persRef> at tea— Chess.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-11">
					<head>11 April 1800</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04-11"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>11. </date><persRef ref="greatheed-bertie">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
								Greatheed</persRef>, and <persRef ref="greatheed-bertie2">his
								son</persRef> call’d upon me this morning— They are just from
							Vienna, upon their return to England.— Recover’d the time I had lost
							yesterday in my translation.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-12">
					<head>12 April 1800</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04-12"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>12. </date><persRef ref="greatheed-bertie;greatheed-ann">M<hi
									rend="superscript">r.</hi> and M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
								Greatheed</persRef>, and <persRef ref="greatheed-bertie2">their
								son</persRef> called this morning to visit <persRef
								key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A.</persRef>—
							Called this afternoon at <persRef ref="augustusfrederick">Prince
								Augustus’s</persRef> lodgings; but did not find him at home— The
							whole evening occupied, like the rest of the day.— At the painted glass
							manufactory in the morning, and at the <persRef ref="anduaga-unknown"
								>Spanish Minister’s</persRef>.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-13">
					<head>13 April 1800</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04-13"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>13. </date>Paid a visit this morning to <persRef
								ref="greatheed-bertie;greatheed-ann">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> and
									M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> Greatheed</persRef>, at the Hotel de
							Russie— Found <persRef ref="engstrom-lars">M: d’Engeström</persRef>, and
								<persRef ref="vonompteda-ludwig">M: Ompteda</persRef> there— M<hi
								rend="superscript">r:</hi> and M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> Greatheed, and
								<persRef ref="greatheed-bertie2">their son</persRef> took tea and
							spent the Evening with <persRef key="adams-louisa-catherine"
								>us</persRef>.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-14">
					<head>14 April 1800</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04-14"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>14. </date>Dined at <persRef ref="brown-charles">D<hi rend="superscript"
									>r:</hi> Brown’s</persRef>, with <persRef ref="greatheed-bertie"
									>M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Greatheed</persRef> and <persRef
								ref="greatheed-ann;greatheed-bertie2">his family</persRef>— <persRef
								ref="u">Miss Bischoffwerder</persRef> &amp; <persRef
								ref="arbuthnot-robert">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Arbuthnot</persRef>.
								<persRef key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
								Adams</persRef> went with M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> G. after dinner
							to visit <persRef ref="vonvoss-sophie">Madame de Voss</persRef> and the
							other ladies. The <persRef ref="alvensleben-philipp">Minister
								Alvensleben</persRef> there in the Evening.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-15">
					<head>15 April 1800</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04-15"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>15. </date><persRef key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>rs:</hi> A</persRef>— went out again this forenoon with
								<persRef ref="greatheed-ann">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
								Greetheed</persRef>.— Walk’d nearly to Charlottenburg. My time is
							now so much engrossed by one subject that I have nothing to say upon any
							other.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-16">
					<head>16 April 1800</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04-16"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>16. </date>The weather uncommonly warm for the season— The trees
							begin already to bud.— One of our horses was seized with a distemper,
							which they call the lock-jaw.— A disorder frequent among horses in this
							Country, though elsewhere unknown.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-17">
					<head>17 April 1800</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04-17"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Court Life and Society (European)</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>17. </date>Finish’d the 9<hi rend="superscript">th:</hi> book of Oberon, and began the 10<hi rend="superscript"
								>th:</hi>— Visit this evening from the <persRef
								ref="anduaga-unknown">Spanish Minister</persRef>; and from <persRef
								ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Sartoris</persRef> and <persRef
								ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Boissier</persRef>— <persRef
								ref="greatheed-ann">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> Greatheed</persRef> was
							presented of the <persRef ref="louiseauguste">queen</persRef>, and to
							the <persRef ref="frederica-louise2">queen mother</persRef>. <persRef
								key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A.</persRef>
							went with her.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-18">
					<head>18 April 1800</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04-18"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>18. </date><persRef ref="augustusfrederick">Prince
								Augustus</persRef>— <persRef ref="greatheed-bertie">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>r:</hi> Greatheed</persRef> and <persRef
								ref="greatheed-ann;greatheed-bertie2">his family</persRef>, <persRef
								ref="brown-charles">D<hi rend="superscript">r.</hi> Brown’s</persRef>
							<persRef
								ref="brown-mary;brown-william5;brown-isabella;brown-fanny;brown-margaret"
								>family</persRef>, <persRef ref="u">Miss Bisschoffwerder</persRef>,
							and <persRef ref="arbuthnot-robert">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
								Arbuthnot</persRef>, &amp; <persRef ref="garlike-benjamin">M<hi
									rend="superscript">r:</hi> Garlike</persRef> dined with us— Play’d a
							game of chess in the evening with D<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Brown— M<hi
								rend="superscript">r:</hi> Greatheed went to spend the evening at the
								<persRef ref="engstrom-lars">Swedish Minister’s</persRef>.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-19">
					<head>19 April 1800</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04-19"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>19. </date>Retriev’d the delay occasion’d in my translation by the
							company we had yesterday.— The weather continues uncommonly warm and
							fine.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-20">
					<head>20 April 1800</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04-20"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Recreation</subject>
						<subject>Court Life and Society (European)</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>20. </date>We dined at <persRef ref="ofarrillyherrera-gonzalo">M<hi
									rend="superscript">r:</hi> O’Farril’s</persRef>, the Spanish Minister’s—
							In the evening went to the play at <persRef ref="cohen-ephraim">M<hi
									rend="superscript">r:</hi> Cohen’s</persRef>. Where we saw Le mariage
							secret, a very pretty comedy, and Les Lutins de Quervoisic: the last
							written by <persRef ref="degenlis-stephanie">Madame de Genlis</persRef>,
							who performed a part herself in the first piece, and play’d on the harp,
							and sung behind the scenes in the second— She is an excellent actress—
							The weather was excessively warm, &amp; the hall very full— <persRef
								key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A</persRef>—
							with <persRef ref="greatheed-ann">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
								Greatheed</persRef>, spent the evening at the <persRef
								ref="frederica-louise2">Queen mother’s</persRef>—and supp’d
							there.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-21">
					<head>21 April 1800</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04-21"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>21. </date><persRef ref="greatheed-bertie">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
								Greatheed</persRef> intended to have gone this morning for Potsdam;
							but waits to spend the evening at <persRef ref="radziwill-anton">Prince
								Radziwill’s</persRef>— Was a little in arrears of my translation
							yesterday which I recovered however this day— Walk now twice a day.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-22">
					<head>22 April 1800</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04-22"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<pb n="294" type="ms"/>
						<p><date>22. </date><persRef ref="greatheed-bertie;greatheed-ann">M<hi
									rend="superscript">r:</hi> and M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
								Greatheed</persRef>, and <persRef ref="greatheed-bertie2">their
								son</persRef> called at noon to take their leave of us, and set out
							immediately afterwards.— Miss Brown, <persRef ref="u">Miss
								Esdorff</persRef> and <persRef ref="u">Miss Dunderfelt</persRef>
							spent part of the Evening with <persRef key="adams-louisa-catherine"
									>M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> Adams</persRef>— I call’d this
							afternoon at the Casino.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-23">
					<head>23 April 1800</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04-23"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Adams Family Residences</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>23. </date>After a very warm day, in the evening was a violent
							thunderstorm; the third already, this spring. <persRef
								key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A.</persRef>
							spent the evening at <persRef ref="brown-mary">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
								Brown</persRef>; I was there about an hour— <persRef ref="u">Miss
								Bisschoffwerder</persRef>, and <persRef ref="arbuthnot-robert">M<hi
									rend="superscript">r:</hi> Arbuthnot</persRef> were there.— Chang’d our
							apartment.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-24">
					<head>24 April 1800</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04-24"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>24. </date>The weather is again very warm— Walk’d in the park
							before dinner, and again towards Evening. Had in the morning a lesson of
							German— Read this Evening to <persRef key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi
									rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A</persRef>— the 9<hi rend="superscript">th:</hi>
							book of the Oberon and a few pages of the mysteries of Udolpho.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-25">
					<head>25 April 1800</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04-25"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>25. </date>I spend as much as three hours now generally in
							walking—the weather being remarkably fine and warm— Wrote a short letter
							this forenoon— In one month more I hope to be reliev’d from what is now
							the greatest pressure upon my time.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-26">
					<head>26 April 1800</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04-26"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>26. </date><persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
								Boissier</persRef> call’d to pay us a visit this forenoon; he is
							going to Vienna— <persRef key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>rs:</hi> A.</persRef> very unwell. Finish’d the 10<hi
								rend="superscript">th:</hi> and began the 11<hi rend="superscript">th:</hi> book of Oberon.— Read a little further in
							the mysteries of Udolpho— Wrote a letter.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-27">
					<head>27 April 1800</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04-27"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>27. </date>Dined with the English <persRef ref="augustusfrederick"
								>prince Augustus</persRef>—<persRef ref="lucchesini-girolamo"
								>Marquis de Lucchesini</persRef>—Mess<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
							<persRef ref="araujo-antonio">Araujo</persRef>, <persRef
								ref="danadia-joao">Anadia</persRef>, <persRef ref="cohen-ephraim"
								>Cohen</persRef>, <persRef ref="u">his son</persRef> and <persRef ref="brown-charles">D<hi
									rend="superscript">r:</hi> Brown</persRef>, were of the company—
								<persRef ref="perponcher-hendrik">Perponcher</persRef> came in,
							while we were at dinner— Came away early and took a long walk in the
							park— Weather, at a high degree of summer heat— <persRef
								key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A.</persRef>
							continues ill.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-28">
					<head>28 April 1800</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04-28"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>28. </date>Weather continues extremely warm— <persRef
								key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A</persRef>—
							yet unwell— Spent the evening at <persRef ref="augustusferdinand">Prince Ferdinand’s</persRef>. Play’d whist with
							the <persRef ref="u">Minister Buchholtz</persRef>, <persRef
								ref="bylandt-willem">Count Byland</persRef>, and <persRef
								ref="voncarmer-johann">Count Carmer</persRef>. <persRef
								ref="philippine">Madame the Landgrave</persRef> was there at the
							beginning of the evening, but went home— The prince talk’d to me again
							about the English, whom he cordially hates.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-29">
					<head>29 April 1800</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04-29"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>29. </date>The three <persRef
								ref="brown-isabella;brown-fanny;brown-margaret">Miss
								Brown’s</persRef> spent the evening with <persRef
								key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A</persRef>—at
							the close of it, we took a walk under the trees— I had been walking
							almost the whole day before— <persRef ref="fahrenheit-daniel">Fahrenheit’s</persRef> thermometer at 76.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-30">
					<head>30 April 1800</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04-30"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>30. </date>The weather has grown much cooler— Took a short walk
							this evening under the trees with <persRef key="adams-louisa-catherine"
									>M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A</persRef>. Read a little to her
							afterwards in the Mysteries of Udolpho.</p>

					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1800-04-xx">
					<head>Day</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1800-04"/><editor
							role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date><hi rend="italic">Day</hi>.</date> Rise generally between 6 and 7.
							Translate Oberon, or give <persRef
								ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Catel</persRef> an hour, untill 10—
							Then breakfast— Renew my translation till between 1 and 2— Walk an hour—
							Dine— Translate again. Walk an hour or two more— Read in the evening to
								<persRef key="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
								A</persRef>— or continue my translation— It engrosses so much my
							time that I am heartily weary of it; but hope before the end of another
							month to finish it.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</body>
	</text>
